                                                                                                               SC on food for kids
          OUR LEGAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	New Delhi, April 25: The Supreme Court has asked all states and Union territories to immediately provide additional nutrition to all children between three months and six years, teenage girls and pregnant and nursing mothers.        
	Vetting the governments nutritional norms revised on February 24, 2009, the apex court asked for compliance reports by January 15 next year.        
	According to the new norms, each child between three months and three years is entitled to food supplement of 500 calories and 12-15gm of protein every day in the form of take-home rations. For the age group of 3-6 years, 500 calories and 12-15gm of protein per child must be made available at anganwadi centres in the form of a hot cooked meal and a morning snack. This has to be implemented by December. For pregnant women and lactating mothers, 600 calories and 18-20gm of protein per day would be provided.                                                                                                                                                                            
